<subSubSection id="C34077D8FF9FB575D156FC9FFD8BFC9A" box="[524,636,820,839]" pageId="8" pageNumber="303" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BE52453FF9FB575D156FC9FFD8BFC9A" box="[524,636,820,839]" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">
(
<figureCitation id="136138D6FF9FB575D148FC9FFD80FC9A" box="[530,631,820,839]" captionStart="Figs 28 – 35" captionStartId="10.[138,176,1476,1495]" captionTargetBox="[138,1026,122,1458]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 28 – 35. Megaselia sihlwaldensis sp. n. male. — 28. palps and proboscis from below; — 29 – 31. hypopygium; — 32. front tarsus; — 33. mid tibia; — 34. hind femur; 5. wing." pageId="8" pageNumber="303">Figs 28–34</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34077D8FF9FB575D3D0FCE4FDB4FC06" pageId="8" pageNumber="303" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BE52453FF9FB575D3D0FCE4FDB4FC06" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">
In the key to the males of the British species (Disney 1989) this species runs to couplet 283, lead 2to 
<taxonomicName id="4C5A5FD0FF9FB575D21DFCC7FDA5FC5E" authority="Wood, 1910" authorityName="Wood" authorityYear="1910" box="[327,594,875,899]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="303" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maura">
<emphasis id="B92EF841FF9FB575D21DFCC7FE45FC5E" bold="true" box="[327,434,876,899]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">M. maura</emphasis>
(Wood, 1910)
</taxonomicName>
, which is immediately distinguished by its well developed hypandrial lobes in contrast to the vestigial lobes of the new species. The abdominal venter and mid and front femora are also paler than those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C5A5FD0FF9FB575D3D0FC6FFF03FC06" box="[138,244,964,987]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="303" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maura">
<emphasis id="B92EF841FF9FB575D3D0FC6FFF03FC06" bold="true" box="[138,244,964,987]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">M. maura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.This couplet is expanded thus:
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34077D8FF9FB574D3D0FC55FECCFA31" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="304" pageId="8" pageNumber="303" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BE52453FF9FB575D3D0FC55FC09FBE9" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">283A Hypandrium with apair of posterior lobes. Abdominal venter dark brownish grey. Mid and front femora yellowish brown or darker ......................... 283</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE52453FF9FB575D3D0FB92FC08FBB3" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">
— Hypandrial lobes vestigial (
<figureCitation id="136138D6FF9FB575D2A4FB92FD7DFB8C" box="[510,650,1081,1105]" captionStart="Figs 28 – 35" captionStartId="10.[138,176,1476,1495]" captionTargetBox="[138,1026,122,1458]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 28 – 35. Megaselia sihlwaldensis sp. n. male. — 28. palps and proboscis from below; — 29 – 31. hypopygium; — 32. front tarsus; — 33. mid tibia; — 34. hind femur; 5. wing." pageId="8" pageNumber="303">Figs 30 &amp;31</figureCitation>
). Venter light grey. Mid and front femora more yellow than brown ................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C5A5FD0FF9FB575D070FBFDFC4AFBB3" box="[810,957,1110,1134]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="303" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sihlwaldensis" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="B92EF841FF9FB575D070FBFDFC4AFBB3" bold="true" box="[810,957,1110,1134]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">sihlwaldensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A21D453AFF9FB575D09EFBFCFC08FBB3" box="[964,1023,1111,1134]" pageId="8" pageNumber="303" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE52453FF9FB575D3D0FB2AFC08FB09" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">
283 Costa at least half length of wing. Hypopygium as in Fig. 492 in Disney (1989), the left hypandrial lobe being clearly longer than the right lobe ..... ............................................................................................ 
<emphasis id="B92EF841FF9FB575D019FB17FC08FB09" bold="true" box="[835,1023,1212,1236]" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">
<emphasis id="B92EF841FF9FB575D019FB17FC57FB09" bold="true" box="[835,928,1212,1236]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">frontalis</emphasis>
(Wood)
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE52453FF9FB575D3D0FB72FC08FAF1" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">
— Costa clearly less than half wing length. Hypopygium as in Fig. 493 in Disney (1989), the hypandrial lobes being more nearly equal in length ............ ............................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C5A5FD0FF9FB575D002FABFFC08FAF1" authority="Wood" authorityName="Wood" box="[856,1023,1300,1324]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="303" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maura">
<emphasis id="B92EF841FF9FB575D002FABFFC08FAF1" bold="true" box="[856,1023,1300,1324]" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">
<emphasis id="B92EF841FF9FB575D002FABFFC56FAF6" bold="true" box="[856,929,1300,1323]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">maura</emphasis>
(Wood)
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE52453FF9FB574D3D0FAE5FECCFA31" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="304" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">
<emphasis id="B92EF841FF9FB575D3D0FAE5FEFFFABB" bold="true" box="[138,264,1358,1382]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">Description</emphasis>
.Male: Frons brown, clearly broader than long, with 66–76 hairs and crowded but very fine microtrichia. Supra-antennal bristles (SAs) about equal in length. The antials lower on frons than anterolaterals, and alittle further from upper SAs than either is from an AL bristle. Pre-ocellars about as far apart as either is from amediolateral bristle, which is at about the same level on frons, and as far apart as upper SAs. Cheek with 5bristles and jowl with two longer ones. The subglobose postpedicels light brown and without subcutaneous pit sensilla (SPS) vesicles. Palps and proboscis as in 
<figureCitation id="136138D6FF9EB574D144FC54FD98FBCA" box="[542,623,1023,1047]" captionStart="Figs 28 – 35" captionStartId="10.[138,176,1476,1495]" captionTargetBox="[138,1026,122,1458]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 28 – 35. Megaselia sihlwaldensis sp. n. male. — 28. palps and proboscis from below; — 29 – 31. hypopygium; — 32. front tarsus; — 33. mid tibia; — 34. hind femur; 5. wing." pageId="9" pageNumber="304">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
, the labella paler than palps and with numerous short spinules below and their combined width about 1.3 times that of postpedicel. Thorax brown. Two notopleural bristles and no cleft in front of these. Mesopleuron bare. Scutellum with an anterior pair of small hairs (about the same as those in middle of scutum) and aposterior pair of bristles. Abdominal tergites brown with hairs, which are clearly longer at rear of T6 (
<figureCitation id="136138D6FF9EB574D1A3FB39FCBEFB77" box="[761,841,1170,1194]" captionStart="Figs 28 – 35" captionStartId="10.[138,176,1476,1495]" captionTargetBox="[138,1026,122,1458]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 28 – 35. Megaselia sihlwaldensis sp. n. male. — 28. palps and proboscis from below; — 29 – 31. hypopygium; — 32. front tarsus; — 33. mid tibia; — 34. hind femur; 5. wing." pageId="9" pageNumber="304">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
). Venter pale grey (
<figureCitation id="136138D6FF9EB574D3FBFB04FF05FB1A" box="[161,242,1199,1223]" captionStart="Figs 28 – 35" captionStartId="10.[138,176,1476,1495]" captionTargetBox="[138,1026,122,1458]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 28 – 35. Megaselia sihlwaldensis sp. n. male. — 28. palps and proboscis from below; — 29 – 31. hypopygium; — 32. front tarsus; — 33. mid tibia; — 34. hind femur; 5. wing." pageId="9" pageNumber="304">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
), and with hairs on segments 3–6. Hypopygium as in 
<figureCitation id="136138D6FF9EB574D012FB04FC32FB1A" box="[840,965,1199,1223]" captionStart="Figs 28 – 35" captionStartId="10.[138,176,1476,1495]" captionTargetBox="[138,1026,122,1458]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 28 – 35. Megaselia sihlwaldensis sp. n. male. — 28. palps and proboscis from below; — 29 – 31. hypopygium; — 32. front tarsus; — 33. mid tibia; — 34. hind femur; 5. wing." pageId="9" pageNumber="304">Figs 29–31</figureCitation>
. Apart from brown patch on mid coxa, legs mainly yellow but hind femur more yellowish brown (
<figureCitation id="136138D6FF9EB574D3B7FB41FECAFADF" box="[237,317,1258,1282]" captionStart="Figs 28 – 35" captionStartId="10.[138,176,1476,1495]" captionTargetBox="[138,1026,122,1458]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 28 – 35. Megaselia sihlwaldensis sp. n. male. — 28. palps and proboscis from below; — 29 – 31. hypopygium; — 32. front tarsus; — 33. mid tibia; — 34. hind femur; 5. wing." pageId="9" pageNumber="304">Fig. 34</figureCitation>
). Fore tarsus with posterodorsal hair palisade on segments 1–4 and 5longer than 4(
<figureCitation id="136138D6FF9EB574D267FAACFE79FAC2" box="[317,398,1287,1311]" captionStart="Figs 28 – 35" captionStartId="10.[138,176,1476,1495]" captionTargetBox="[138,1026,122,1458]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 28 – 35. Megaselia sihlwaldensis sp. n. male. — 28. palps and proboscis from below; — 29 – 31. hypopygium; — 32. front tarsus; — 33. mid tibia; — 34. hind femur; 5. wing." pageId="9" pageNumber="304">Fig. 32</figureCitation>
). Dorsal hair palisade of mid tibia extends about 0.6 times its length (
<figureCitation id="136138D6FF9EB574D256FA8FFEACFAE1" box="[268,347,1316,1340]" captionStart="Figs 28 – 35" captionStartId="10.[138,176,1476,1495]" captionTargetBox="[138,1026,122,1458]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 28 – 35. Megaselia sihlwaldensis sp. n. male. — 28. palps and proboscis from below; — 29 – 31. hypopygium; — 32. front tarsus; — 33. mid tibia; — 34. hind femur; 5. wing." pageId="9" pageNumber="304">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
). Hairs below basal half of hind femur about as long as those of anteroventral row of outer half (
<figureCitation id="136138D6FF9EB574D2AEFAE9FDB3FA87" box="[500,580,1346,1370]" captionStart="Figs 28 – 35" captionStartId="10.[138,176,1476,1495]" captionTargetBox="[138,1026,122,1458]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 28 – 35. Megaselia sihlwaldensis sp. n. male. — 28. palps and proboscis from below; — 29 – 31. hypopygium; — 32. front tarsus; — 33. mid tibia; — 34. hind femur; 5. wing." pageId="9" pageNumber="304">Fig. 34</figureCitation>
). Hind tibia with at least adozen differentiated posterodorsal hairs and spinules of apical combs simple. Wings (
<figureCitation id="136138D6FF9EB574D0DFFAF4FC26FAAA" box="[901,977,1375,1399]" captionStart="Figs 28 – 35" captionStartId="10.[138,176,1476,1495]" captionTargetBox="[138,1026,122,1458]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 28 – 35. Megaselia sihlwaldensis sp. n. male. — 28. palps and proboscis from below; — 29 – 31. hypopygium; — 32. front tarsus; — 33. mid tibia; — 34. hind femur; 5. wing." pageId="9" pageNumber="304">Fig. 35</figureCitation>
) 1.25 mm long. Costal index 0.40. Costal ratios 3.3:1.3:1. Costal cilia (of section 3) 0.08 mm long. Hair at base of vein 3well developed. With 2axillary bristles, the outer being very slightly longer than the outer costal cilium. Sc not reaching R1. Haltere brown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
